(We shall flow a river unto thee, and teeming with souls shall it ever be.)</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/udaeon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Daeon</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I live here.... get out.</span><br> <font color=#000033>(3/21/01 8:05:56 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.bellatlantic.net/~mezner/hamster2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Goshan's Topic of the day - Using slow</span><hr size=1> Shaman slow is a good chunk better than ours up until Forlorn Deeds, which is a level 57 spell I believe.  At that point, their slow is only a few percentage points better than ours...  Don't get me wrong, I'd still rather have that extra slow from the shaman spell - but at that point, an enchanter can slow pretty damn well, also.  I would assume if a shaman and enchanter were both in the group, that they would be able to work something out in regards to alternating, to perhaps conserve on mana for both of them.<br>
<br>
Right now, if I'm slowing, I find that to be the single biggest mana drain in a group besides $@&^n Swift Like the Wind.  DAMN that spell... WAY too much of my mana is spent recasting SLTW... <br>
<br>
Somebody get me my epic!  lol<br>
